---
import AboutHeroImage from '../assets/blog-placeholder-about.jpg';
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About Tokyo Mix Style"
	description="Why Tokyo Mix Style exists: mixing Japanese fashion brands with sustainable secondhand style."
	pubDate={new Date('Jun 21 2026')}
	heroImage={AboutHeroImage}
>
	<p>
		Tokyo Mix Style started from a simple observation: Japan makes some of the best everyday
		clothing in the world — UNIQLO's basics, Muji's quiet, well-made staples, and a long list of
		smaller and higher-end labels most people outside Japan have barely heard of. At the same
		time, secondhand and vintage shopping has become one of the few fashion trends that's actually
		good for the planet. Almost nobody was putting the two together.
	</p>

	<p>
		That's the idea behind "Tokyo Mix Style": take clean, dependable Japanese basics and mix them
		with secondhand pieces that bring in texture, history, and a bit of personality. New clothes
		where it matters, old clothes where it adds character — and a wardrobe that ends up costing
		less and lasting longer than buying everything new from a single brand.
	</p>

	<p>
		This site is run on a simple set of rules: every outfit guide and comparison is something we'd
		actually wear, every product recommendation is chosen because it's genuinely good (not because
		it pays the most commission), and every secondhand styling tip comes from real trial and error
		— including plenty of thrift-store misses along the way.
	</p>

	<p>
		If you're curious about Japanese fashion brands but unsure how to wear them, or you already
		love thrifting and want to mix in a few well-chosen new basics, this is the right place to
		start. New guides go up roughly once a week — see the <a href="/blog">latest posts</a> to dive
		in.
	</p>

	<p>
		<em
			>Tokyo Mix Style participates in affiliate programs, which means some links on this site may
			earn a small commission at no extra cost to you. We only recommend products we'd genuinely
			choose ourselves.</em
		>
	</p>
</Layout>
